ANCOVA

Rmcorr and ANCOVA

V4 vs V6 group 4

Sample observations for plotting

RMCORR: assesses the intra-individual or longitudinal change. To be able to plot, we sample randomly roughly 10 people from the dataset.

# set seed to make the sampling reproducible
set.seed(123)
group_4_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(group_4)), size = 10)
group_4_sample <- group_4[group_4$Participant %in% group_4[group_4_ind,1],]

V6_V4_sample.rmc <- rmcorr(Participant, V6, V4, group_4_sample)
print(V6_V4_sample.rmc)
## 
## Repeated measures correlation
## 
## r
## -0.3968902
## 
## degrees of freedom
## 29
## 
## p-value
## 0.02705829
## 
## 95% confidence interval
## -0.6664521 -0.03555664
plot(V6_V4_sample.rmc, overall = T, lty=2, xlab = 'V6', ylab = 'V4')

COMMENT: r = -0.3968902 and p-value = 0.02705829, there is a negative significant relationship between V6 and V4 intra-individuals, which is weaker than the relationship calculated with the regression line (gray line).

All group 4 observations output

# Overall rmcorr output
rmc.out <- rmcorr(Participant, V4, V6, group_4)
print(rmc.out)
## 
## Repeated measures correlation
## 
## r
## -0.1539083
## 
## degrees of freedom
## 8930
## 
## p-value
## 1.782206e-48
## 
## 95% confidence interval
## -0.1740937 -0.1335936

COMMENT: Small effect sizes for rmcorr (r = -0.15) may be caused by heterogenous slopes (poor model fit), or by consistently near-zero slopes across subjects, or by restriction in the range of one or both measures.
